It’s a kind of duality — as if time and frequency are pulling on opposite ends of a rope.
And as a special case, if you use a delta function — which is infinitely narrow in time — its Fourier transform becomes perfectly flat, spread across all frequencies.
On the other hand, a Gaussian function is balanced — it’s the only shape where both the time and frequency profiles remain Gaussian.
So visually, scaling is not just a math trick — it’s a powerful way to understand how functions behave in both domains.

